<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06180043 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06180043 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; IMMIGRATION; WEALTH; FOREIGN; INVESTMENT; LAW; CHANGE; BUSINESS; INDUSTRY;EMPLOYMENT; INCREASE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The green card, key to legal immigration in the United States, can be had bywealthy foreign investors who shell out $1 million to create 10 new jobs.;   The new law is a potential U.S. business bonanza that will be the subject of aseminar today in San Francisco.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GOT A MILLION? WELCOME TO AMERICAGETTING GREEN CARD NOW EASIER FOR RICH  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The law has been criticized by some who say it flies counter to traditionalU.S. immigration policies, typified in the famous Emma Lazarus poem: &quot;Give meyour tired, your poor, your huddled masses yearning to breathe free.&quot;;    Eventhough the law is more of a &quot;give me your rich&quot; approach, supporters note thatit's already law in Canada and Australia.;    Ordinarily, only those withimmediate relatives in the United States can hope to immigrate without delaysthat could last years.;    But the law, tucked into the 1990 Immigration Act,will allow some immigrants to bypass that process if they pledge at least $1million to create 10 jobs for U.S. citizens.;    The law takes effect Oct. 1,1991, and there are already 600 immigrants interested, said James Mayock, animmigration lawyer scheduled to speak at the seminar.;    Immigrants admittedunder the program would be allowed to bring their immediate families ontemporary residency cards. Two years later, they would have to prove they hadinvested the $1 million and created 10 jobs for U.S. citizens to get apermanent residency card, or green card.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  San Francisco  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910628  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH